We'd already done a deep dive. He goes, what do you think about it? And I said, I kind of dug up the research we did on market neutral from that 2011 paper. And I said, the problem there is just mathematically, it's going to be difficult for any linear approach to kind of disaggregate really the factors on the long side versus the factors on the short side. And so the net result... At least what we found is, it ends up looking a lot like cash or cash plus, kind of levered cash plus type instruments, maybe some short ball effect in there. And sure enough, at this point, the ETF fact sheet was like 80% TLT, BIL, SHY, like all these cash ETFs. And I told him, I was like, I think that's probably what's happening here. And we turned down, you know, we turned down money, because we just said, you have to treat that as an artifact, you know, first of all, when you can, you know, statistically, when you know, when you dip down into, you know, as R squared goes down, kind of the confidence and roll around, it goes up, I was like, but then, you know, also, you look under the hood, and it's really just, you know, kind of levered cash or short ball, I was like, you're better off actually, you know, going direct. And so market neutral is one. And that was from a statistical perspective.
